Financial Advice on Effective Portfolio Diversification to Lower Risk and Maximize Returns on Investements















Philosophy


Our ultimate objective in using a systematic and disciplined investment process is to capture the financial goals unique to each client.
Wallington Asset Management believes in an active approach to investment management with an emphasis on quality and effective diversification. A systematic and disciplined investment process is utilized as we strive to achieve, over the long-term, a total return that exceeds a client’s benchmark return based upon popular stock and bond indexes. Commensurate with this return objective is the assumption of a reasonable and conservative risk posture through investments in high-quality common stocks, fixed income securities and/or money market instruments. While a prescribed set of guidelines determined by the client's investment policy governs the allocation of investment funds to the various asset classes, these allocations may be adjusted over time due to fluctuations in individual asset values or when our analysis indicates a fundamental imbalance in the risk-return spectrum.



    	  		Photo: Scalini
    	  	










 



What is a Fixed Income Philopsopy for High Quality Bonds and Conservative Maturity Structures?















Philosophy: Fixed Income


The defining characteristics of Wallington Asset Management’s fixed income philosophy are the use of high quality bonds and conservative maturity structures.
Wallington Asset Management utilizes a four phase approach in the management of fixed income portfolios. First, a fixed income strategy is designed to meet each client’s long-term investment objectives. This is more difficult than generally believed. Each client’s liquidity needs, tax considerations and time horizon constraints are entwined with the investment objective defined for the portfolio. Objectives may include any goal in the spectrum from stability of principal and income to the maximization of long-term nominal returns.
Once these objectives have been defined, Wallington Asset Management will then establish a duration range to manage the sensitivity of each client’s bond portfolio value to changes in interest rates. Since most research evidence indicates that a conservative bond maturity structure allows for the capture of most of the returns offered in longer-dated maturities while incurring proportionately less interest rate risk, our preference is to focus on the intermediate term maturities.
The third phase of our fixed income management employs the use of prudent portfolio strategies on an on-going basis. These strategies are drawn from macroeconomic analysis as well as yield curve and fundamental credit analysis. Our tactics may take the form of composite duration and convexity adjustment, shifts to undervalued sectors, and individual bond swaps. We seek to reap the rewards of credit upgrades and to avoid the risk of credit downgrades.
Finally, we continually monitor the performance of each holding as well as that holding’s contribution to the total interest rate risk of the fixed income portfolio. We believe this fourth step is crucial as we strive to maximize returns within a predetermined level of risk.



    	  		Photo: Scalini
    	  	










 



Financial Services for Personal, Trusts and Institutions Constructing Equity Portfolios with Value and Growth Stocks















Philosophy: Common Stock


The distinguishing characteristic of Wallington Asset Management’s equity philosophy is the employment of both value and growth stocks in constructing equity portfolios.
Wallington Asset Management employs both value and growth stock philosophies in the construction and management of equity portfolios. This blended investment philosophy toward common stocks originates from the ongoing debate between value and growth stock adherents and the inordinate amount of risk incurred when either value or growth selection is used exclusively. We believe that simultaneous investment in both value and growth stocks results in enhanced performance and serves to reduce the risk of under-performance associated with a stock portfolio exposed solely to the characteristics of either growth stocks or value stocks.
Our strategy is to select stocks of companies in those instances where we believe the market is underestimating the total return potential from holding such a security. Conversely, we eliminate those securities we believe are priced at a level reflecting unrealistic expectations. Each client’s equity portfolio maintains diversification but not in strict accordance with the sector weights reflected in the popular indexes. It is our ultimate objective to preserve capital and to outperform the market on a risk-adjusted basis over the long-term utilizing the S&P 500 Stock Index as the benchmark portfolio against which performance will be measured.



    	  		Photo: Scalini
    	  	










 



Create a Well Defined Investment Policy to Reach Long Term Financial Goals for Retirement















Philosophy: Formulation


Each investment portfolio, whether for the individual or the institutional investor, requires a well-defined investment policy to successfully fulfill financial goals over the long-term.
As independent investment professionals, we are available to work closely with our clients and their advisors to establish a suitable investment policy. In this process, items such as risk, expected rates of return, cash flow requirements and time horizons are discussed to formulate guidelines by which each investment portfolio will be managed. Specifically, it is this phase of the investment management process which dictates the general allocation of investment funds to the various asset classes (i.e., equities, fixed income, and cash). Consequently, these guidelines serve as a benchmark to realistically evaluate future investment performance.



    	  		Photo: Scalini
    	  	












