Wallington Asset Management LLC



 OVERVIEW



Date Founded


1988




Headquarters


8900 Keystone Crossing Suite 1015 Indianapolis In United States 46240-2134




Employees (Worldwide)


17




Industries


Investment Services & Portfolio Management




Company Description


Wallington Asset Management employs a GARP equity investment approach that is based on both value and growth investment strategies. The firm believes that simultaneous investment in value and growth stocks results in enhanced performance and reduces the risk of under performance associated with a stock portfolio exposed solely to the characteristics of either growth stocks or value stocks. They select the stocks of companies in which the total return potential from holding such a security is underestimated in the market. Wallington eliminates securities that are priced at a level that reflects unrealistic expectations. Each client's equity portfolio maintains diversification but not in strict accordance with the sector weights reflected in the popular indexes. Wallington's objective is to preserve capital and to outperform the market on a risk-adjusted basis over the long-term using the S&P 500 as the benchmark. Though not limited by sector, the firm tends to invest in the stocks of US large-cap companies in the health technology, producer manufacturing, consumer non-durables, electronic technology and technology services sectors. Wallington also invests in Europe, the Middle East and Asia. The firm maintains a very low turnover rate.Wallington manages fixed-income portfolios using a four-phase approach. First, a fixed-income strategy is designed to meet each client's long-term objectives. Then establish a duration range to manage the sensitivity of each client's bond portfolio value to changes in interest rates. Wallington prefers to focus on intermediate-term maturities. The third phase of the firm's fixed-income management strategy employs the use of prudent portfolio strategies on an on-going basis. These strategies are drawn from macroeconomic analysis and from yield curve and fundamental credit analysis. Wallington's strategies may take the form of composite duration and convexity adjustment, shifts to undervalued sectors and individual bond swaps. They seek the rewards of credit upgrades while avoiding the risk of credit downgrades. Finally, Wallington continually monitors the performance of each holding as well as that holding's contribution to the total interest rate risk of the fixed-income portfolio.




